ish Brendan, Caitlin, Niamh.","Irish: variant of   Fitzsimmons  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitzsimmons","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of <b>Fitzsimon</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + either of the personal names <i>Simon</i> or <i>Sigmund</i> (see   Simon  ), ‘son of <i>Simon</i> or <i>Sigmund</i>’. The name is also found in the Gaelicized form <b>Mac Síomóin</b>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":29,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":54,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret FitzSimons was born in 1261, in England. She married Robert Langton in 1281, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1325, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1261–1325":"1261–1325","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1333":"1333","1256":"1256","1285":"1285","1261":"1261","1281":"1281","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England":"Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1261–1325":"1261–1325","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1315":"1315","1325":"